  "why": "The paper uses standard adversarial attack methods (FGSM, BIM, DeepFool) and data augmentation techniques to generate test inputs for image and audio models. These methods, particularly the adversarial attacks, create fine-grained numerical perturbations. However, the paper does not mention any steps taken to enforce the input format constraints of the resulting data. For instance, when generating adversarial images for the MNIST dataset, there is no mention of clipping pixel values to the valid [0, 255] range or rounding them to integers. Without these enforcement steps, perturbations that trigger a failure in an in-memory floating-point representation might be altered or lost when the image is serialized to a standard file format (e.g., a pixel value of 255.8 would be clipped to 255, and 150.3 would be rounded to 150). This means that the failures identified by the fuzzer may not be reproducible from a saved input file under realistic conditions.",
